on the Move Prize Research & Insights Announcements Donate About How We Work How We Work Our mission is to advance equitable, meaningful education that prepares every Boston student to activate their power and shape their We work at the classroom, school, and system levels to accelerate improvement in Boston’s We combine strategic grantmaking, content expertise, and collaborative implementation to drive impact in Boston We leverage the body of knowledge, relationships, and trust we have built in the Boston education landscape to advance equity and create EdVestors works in three ways to to advance equitable, meaningful education that prepares every Boston student to activate their power and shape their future: Activating people and resources Learning and iterating in context Influencing system change Our Values Our values drive our efforts and shape our relationships with each other and our Just We aim to advance racial equity in our organization, schools, and communities, as we continue to learn about and interrogate white supremacy culture and systemic We commit to thoughtfully assessing our role in upholding systems of oppression, to working in community toward mutual accountability, and to remaining optimistic as we pursue equity in education for our In Community We care for our colleagues and We believe the greatest potential for impact comes from working together and that success flows from listening, learning, and working in Thoughtful We are reflective, critical, and We are sensitive to the needs and aspirations of those we work with and carefully consider the impact of our Committed We are dedicated to making a difference in the lives of Boston We invest in sustainable practices that create deep, meaningful, and Optimistic We believe that an equitable future for our students and ourselves is We bring joy, hope, and a desire to be better Equity Statement Equity is explicitly at the core of our and actions in pursuit of every young person in Boston having access to meaningful Equity Definitions Adapting resources from the Annie Casey Foundation and Stanford Social Innovation Review , we define equity as access for all to opportunities, networks, resources and supports that enable them to To be achieved and sustained, equity needs to be thought of as a structural and systemic Adapting resources from Center for Assessment and Policy Development , Race Forward Center for Social Inclusion , and Equity in the Center , we define racial equity as a combination of: Equitable opportunities and outcomes for everyone regardless of race or ethnicity Meaningful involvement of those most impacted by racial inequity and racism in decision making and implementation Addressing root causes of inequities and systemic oppression, where we perpetuate them, and how we can work to eliminate them, leading to racial Equity Approach We dedicate resources toward our internal and external commitments to We articulate and share our equity commitments with our We center the voices, interests, and needs of those most impacted by our work in our We refine and evolve our goals, approach, and commitments related to equity through our monthly DEI (Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion) Team, affinity groups, and our annual organizational planning Our mission is to advance equitable, meaningful education that prepares every Boston student to activate their power and shape their EdVestors is a (c)(3) nonprofit Donate today ! They began a dedicated search that resulted in finding some interesting solutions… all of which seemed to miss the Namely, they were expensive, couldn’t overcome the “last mile” of core integration (many didn’t even know what a core was!), and couldn’t bridge the cultural communication gap between community financial institutions and Finally, Kyle and Jack met Tina Baker (CPO) and Terry McMullen (COO) with Kiva Group, who had developed microservices that seamlessly integrated with major core banking providers and enabled various use cases for their clients, like call centers and banking Their conversations quickly went from “can we partner to provide a service?” to “what if we could drive significant change together for the whole community financial institution ecosystem?” The idea took off to leverage key integration technology that was helping a few larger institutions in order to create a universal integration platform in the cloud for
